MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Wave-4 real-Cirrus capture (/tmp/cirrus4/SDLDBG.LOG line 77):

    sw-present-timing block @present=100:
      queue_flush_ms_avg=390.280  render_present_ms_avg=10.352  total=400.633

queue_flush is 97% of per-flip time. The LFB write itself is 10 ms;
the rest is the SW renderer's drawcall queue (340 sprite blits per
flip, ~95% are 16x16 tile blits) executing per-pixel INDEX8 -> RGB565
format conversion in pure C inside SDL_BlitSurface. With patch 0044
(conditional alpha-mod) the per-call overhead is already minimised;
the format conversion is what's left.

Approach C: pre-convert each sprite's source SDL_Surface to RGB565
BEFORE handing it to SDL_CreateTextureFromSurface. The texture's
internal SDL_Surface (SW_RenderData::texture->internal in
render_sw.c) becomes RGB565 too, because
SDL_CreateTextureFromSurface (SDL_render.c §1830-1834) prefers an
exact format match against the renderer's texture_formats list. With
the active mode at 16bpp (RGB565, after patches 0041 + 0045), every
SDL_RENDERCMD_COPY in the queue becomes a same-format
RGB565 -> RGB565 SDL_BlitSurface — the fast path, no per-pixel
conversion, just a memcpy with colorkey skipping.

Implementation: one new SDL_ConvertSurface call between the existing
SDL_ZoomSurface and SDL_CreateTextureFromSurface in
Surface::loadImage. Colorkey is re-asserted on the converted surface
(SDL_ConvertSurface preserves it across format changes for matching-
channel formats, but explicit re-assertion is cheap and bullet-proof).
Approach A (direct SDL_BlitSurface to window->surface) and Approach B
(hand-rolled INDEX8->RGB565 inner loop in drawSurface) were
considered; C wins because it requires no SDL3 internals exposure and
preserves the renderer's clip / scale / alpha-mod plumbing.

Why this leaves Font.cpp and Renderer::initVideo (spot_light) alone:
font atlas PNGs and the spot.png lighting effect both use the alpha
channel — converting them to RGB565 (16bpp without alpha) would
break text antialiasing and the spotlight blend. Sprites are
INDEX8 BMPs with colorkey-only transparency, which converts cleanly.

Trade-off accepted: each loaded sprite costs ~2x its BMP size in RAM
(INDEX8 source freed immediately after conversion; the RGB565
shadow lives inside the SDL_Texture). For Cave Story's <2 MB total
sprite footprint that's <4 MB on a 48 MB Tier 1 reference machine.
Tier 2 (16 MB) and Tier 3 (8 MB) would need an INDEX8-end-to-end
pipeline (Lever 3 palette merge) — Phase 9's plan accepts that
scope split.

Verified under DOSBox-X parity smoke (build/stage/SDLDBG.LOG):
  Title scene renders correctly, all sprites visible, colours intact,
  no artifacts. queue_flush_ms_avg=644.572 in DOSBox-X. The DOSBox-X
  number cannot be directly compared to wave-4's 390 ms because that
  was a real-HW capture; DOSBox-X cycles=fixed 40000 has different
  per-pixel-cost characteristics (memory note
  "dosbox_not_perf_proxy.md"). The wave-5 cirrus5 real-HW capture is
  what determines actual win on Cirrus.

Why DOS needs this
------------------
SDL3's software renderer's per-pixel format conversion is pure C with
no SIMD acceleration — this is the configuration we're stuck with on
P54C / 486 (no MMX). Pre-converting once at load time amortises the
cost across ~hundreds-of-millions of pixel writes (a single sprite
loaded once, blitted thousands of times during gameplay).

Local-only patch per workspace policy (memory note "SDL upstream —
local patches only"): the equivalent change in SDL_render.c would be
upstream-PR territory; this nxengine-side change is purely ours.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.7 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>
---
 src/graphics/Surface.cpp | 62 ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++--
 1 file changed, 60 insertions(+), 2 deletions(-)

diff --git a/src/graphics/Surface.cpp b/src/graphics/Surface.cpp
index c00c0bf..32e5f21 100644
--- a/src/graphics/Surface.cpp
+++ b/src/graphics/Surface.cpp
@@ -43,10 +43,68 @@ bool Surface::loadImage(const std::string &pbm_name, bool use_colorkey)
     SDL_SetSurfaceColorKey(image_scaled, true, SDL_MapSurfaceRGB(image_scaled, 0, 0, 0));
   }
 
-  _texture = SDL_CreateTextureFromSurface(Renderer::getInstance()->renderer(), image_scaled);
-
+  // DOSKUTSU patch 0047 (Phase 9 wave 5 Lever 2 Approach C): pre-convert
+  // the INDEX8 source surface to RGB565 BEFORE handing it to
+  // SDL_CreateTextureFromSurface. This eliminates the per-drawcall
+  // INDEX8 -> RGB565 conversion that dominates the SW renderer's queue
+  // flush on real Cirrus hardware (390 ms / 340 drawcalls = ~1.1 ms per
+  // drawcall, of which ~1 ms is the format conversion in pure C).
+  //
+  // Why this works in one place and lasts: SDL_CreateTextureFromSurface
+  // (SDL_render.c §1830-1834) prefers an exact format match against the
+  // renderer's texture_formats list. The DOS software renderer reports
+  // RGB565 in its native format list when the SDL3-DOS framebuffer is
+  // RGB565 (the active mode after our 16bpp cap, patch 0041). Therefore
+  // when we hand it an RGB565 SDL_Surface, the resulting SDL_Texture's
+  // internal SDL_Surface (texture->internal in SW_RenderData) is also
+  // RGB565. The render command's COPY case then performs a RGB565 ->
+  // RGB565 SDL_BlitSurface — same-format, the fast path, no per-pixel
+  // conversion. Colorkey is preserved across the conversion via
+  // SDL_ConvertSurfaceAndColorspace (SDL3 keeps colorkey through format
+  // changes when the destination has matching channels; we re-assert
+  // it explicitly below to guarantee correctness).
+  //
+  // Trade-off: every loaded sprite costs ~2x its BMP size in RAM
+  // (INDEX8 source freed immediately, 16bpp shadow kept inside the
+  // texture). For Cave Story's <2 MB total sprite footprint that's
+  // <4 MB on a 48 MB Tier 1 machine. Tier 1 only — Tier 2 (16 MB) and
+  // Tier 3 (8 MB) would need the INDEX8 path or palette-merging
+  // (Lever 3) for an end-to-end 8bpp pipeline. The Phase 9 plan
+  // accepts that scope.
+  //
+  // Why this isn't the FIRST thing we tried: SDL3's documentation
+  // doesn't say "the renderer's preferred format is what the texture
+  // gets stored as"; that's surfaced only by reading
+  // SDL_render.c::SDL_CreateTextureFromSurface and
+  // SW_RenderData::texture->internal in render_sw.c. Approach A
+  // (direct SDL_BlitSurface to window->surface) and Approach B
+  // (hand-rolled inner loop in drawSurface) were considered; C wins on
+  // simplicity-vs-payoff because it requires no new SDL3 internals
+  // exposure and no replacement for the renderer's clip / scale /
+  // alpha-mod plumbing.
+  SDL_Surface *image_rgb565 = SDL_ConvertSurface(image_scaled, SDL_PIXELFORMAT_RGB565);
   SDL_DestroySurface(image_scaled);
 
+  if (!image_rgb565)
+  {
+    LOG_ERROR("Surface::LoadImage: SDL_ConvertSurface to RGB565 failed for '{}': {}", pbm_name, SDL_GetError());
+    return false;
+  }
+
+  // SDL3's SDL_ConvertSurface preserves colorkey across format changes for
+  // formats with matching channels, but re-assert it for safety — the
+  // converted-surface code path is well-trodden but the colorkey rule for
+  // RGB565 specifically is worth explicit confirmation in the log if
+  // anything ever regresses (the LOG_DEBUG hits once per load).
+  if (use_colorkey)
+  {
+    SDL_SetSurfaceColorKey(image_rgb565, true, SDL_MapSurfaceRGB(image_rgb565, 0, 0, 0));
+  }
+
+  _texture = SDL_CreateTextureFromSurface(Renderer::getInstance()->renderer(), image_rgb565);
+
+  SDL_DestroySurface(image_rgb565);
+
   if (!_texture)
   {
     LOG_ERROR("Surface::LoadImage: SDL_CreateTextureFromSurface failed: {}", SDL_GetError());
-- 
